-- 
Statoil Buys Forties at Higher Price; BFOE Loadings to Decline

-- B y   S h e r r y   S u
-- 
2011-06-09T16:11:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-09/statoil-buys-forties-at-higher-price-bfoe-loadings-to-decline.html
Statoil ASA bought  North Sea  Forties
crude at a higher price. BP Plc failed to sell Russian Urals for
the third day even after it lowered the offer.  Daily exports of the four North Sea crudes that make the
benchmark Dated Brent price are scheduled to fall 11 percent in
July, according to loading programs obtained by Bloomberg News.  North Sea  Statoil bought one cargo of Forties for June 28 to June 30
from Total SA at 85 cents a barrel above the cash cost of North
Sea crudes for August, compared with a premium of 50 cents
yesterday, according to a survey of traders and brokers
monitoring the Platts trading window.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc was unable to buy a shipment for June
22 to June 24 at 65 cents more than Dated Brent, while Morgan
Stanley failed to buy a cargo for June 28 to June 30 at 60 cents
above the benchmark, the survey showed.  Reported North Sea market activity typically occurs during
the Platts window, which ends at 4:30 p.m. London time. Before
the window, Forties loading in 10 to 21 days cost 61 cents more
than Dated Brent, compared with 64 cents yesterday, according to
Bloomberg data.  Brent for July settlement traded at $118.98 a barrel on the
London-based ICE Futures  Europe  exchange at the close of the
window, up from $117.84 yesterday. The August contract was at
$118.49, 49 cents less than July.  Shipments of Brent, Forties, Oseberg and Ekofisk will total
30.05 million barrels, or 969,355 barrels a day, next month, the
plans showed. That compares with 32.5 million barrels, or 1.08
million barrels a day, in June. Exports of Forties for July will
total 18 cargoes, six less than this month.  Mediterranean/Urals  BP didn’t manage to sell 100,000 metric tons of Urals for
June 30 to July 4 delivery in northwest Europe at $2.25 a barrel
below Dated Brent, 10 cents lower than its offer yesterday,
according to the survey.  In the Mediterranean, Glencore International AG failed to
buy 80,000 tons of Urals for June 19 to June 23 at $1.85 a
barrel less than Dated Brent, the survey showed.  Daily exports of Azeri Light crude from a port in  Turkey 
will fall 5.3 percent next month, according to a loading
schedule.  Shipments for July will total 22.8 million barrels, or
735,484 barrels a day, the plan showed. This compares with 23.2
million barrels, or 776,667 barrels a day, in June.  Saudi Aramco , the world’s largest state-owned oil company,
will supply full contractual volumes of crude to customers in
Europe next month, according to two refinery officials.  Hellenic Petroleum SA bought 85,000 tons of Caspian CPC
Blend crude from Gunvor International BV through a spot tender,
according to two traders who participate in the market. The
cargo is for June 25 to July 5 delivery to the Greek
Mediterranean ports of Pachi Megara or Thessaloniki.  West Africa  Indonesia ’s state-owned PT Pertamina issued a tender to buy
low-sulfur crude, including West African grades, for delivery in
August, an official document obtained today by Bloomberg News
showed. The tender is scheduled to be awarded on June 14.  To contact the reporter on this story:
